WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:10.470
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today&nbsp;
we're going to look at the algorithm of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:10.470 --> 00:00:16.410
finding the square root of a number. This&nbsp;
is an important operation that goes back&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:22.410
to antiquity—to the ancient Greeks, to&nbsp;
the Chinese, to the Arabs, Babylonians,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:29.760
and even to the Hindus. It's important because&nbsp;
it's the basis for solving quadratic equations.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:35.070
Without being able to take a square root, the&nbsp;
quadratic formula doesn't make too much sense.

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:43.110
Let's start off with an example and show you&nbsp;
three different approaches to the subject.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.110 --> 00:00:48.990
The one that we're mainly interested in is&nbsp;
one developed by the Hindu mathematicians,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.990 --> 00:00:53.280
and it's a very practical algorithm that you&nbsp;
can try yourself after you've learned it.

00:00:53.280 --> 00:01:03.360
Alright, so here's an example: 523 squared&nbsp;
equals this number, 2703529. We say that 523 is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:09.600
the square root of this number. The idea is we are&nbsp;
given this number to start with, and we're trying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:17.040
to find the square root. One way of approaching&nbsp;
it, which is a good way for public school students&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:26.400
to start thinking about the subject, is to make&nbsp;
some guesses. 500 squared is 250,000, while 600&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:33.570
squared is 360,000, so the real answer must lie&nbsp;
somewhere in between those two guesses. Then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:38.640
can make some further guesses, keep on squaring&nbsp;
the guesses that we have, and see if we're getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:46.140
bigger or less than our starting number, and&nbsp;
eventually we'll zero in on our number 523.

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:52.440
Here's another method that goes back to the&nbsp;
ancient Babylonians. Basically, the idea is this:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:58.920
suppose that x squared equals n is the equation&nbsp;
we're trying to solve. So what we do is we make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:09.930
an initial guess x1, we compute n divided by x1,&nbsp;
then we set x2 to be the average of these two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:18.870
numbers—the average of x1 and n divided by x1—and&nbsp;
then we repeat the process using x2 instead of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:27.480
x1. The idea is that if x1 is exactly the square&nbsp;
root, then n divided by x1 will be equal to x1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:33.660
and these two numbers will be equal. Otherwise,&nbsp;
one of them will be less than and one of them will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:39.570
be bigger than the square root, and so averaging&nbsp;
those two numbers, it's a relatively good guess&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.570 --> 00:02:47.190
for the square root. If we keep doing that, then&nbsp;
we approach the square root value. This method&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:52.410
is essentially the same as Newton's method,&nbsp;
discovered by Isaac Newton, which is taught&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:58.770
in calculus courses. Without going into too much&nbsp;
detail, the idea is roughly that we have a curve&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.770 --> 00:03:04.530
and we want to find its zero. Say the curve is&nbsp;
represented by the equation x squared minus n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:04.530 --> 00:03:12.420
then what we do is we take one guess here and find&nbsp;
the tangent, see where that tangent intersects the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:18.030
x-axis, and then that's our next guess. Then&nbsp;
the next tangent gives us the next guess, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.030 --> 00:03:25.200
so on. It turns out that this Babylonian method,&nbsp;
four thousand years ago, is essentially Newton's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:31.860
method in this particular case. However, for&nbsp;
pen-and-paper calculations, or even by computer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:39.210
it's a little bit slow in the sense that you&nbsp;
have to rely on dividing and repeated divisions.

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:41.730
So let's have a look at the third method,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.730 --> 00:03:47.550
which is due to the Hindus. This Vedic&nbsp;
method relies on the following identity:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:57.120
(x + y) squared is x squared plus we can&nbsp;
write the rest in this form: 2x + y times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.120 --> 00:04:03.450
y. The basic idea is that we're going to have an&nbsp;
initial approximation, and then we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:11.730
guess how much we have to adjust that initial&nbsp;
approximation by computing a term like this.

00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:22.170
So in our example of 523 squared, let's make the&nbsp;
following observations: 500 squared is 250,000,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.170 --> 00:04:31.740
okay, so that's less than our number n. 520&nbsp;
squared will be, according to this law here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:42.360
it's 500 squared plus 2 times 500 plus 20, so&nbsp;
1,000 plus 20 times 20. It's a way of thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:48.090
of how you go from here to here. What you're&nbsp;
doing is you're adding this new component,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:55.530
and that turns out to be this number here.&nbsp;
Then the next stage, 523 all squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.530 --> 00:05:00.450
well that's what we have at the previous&nbsp;
stage, that's 520 squared right there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.450 --> 00:05:08.430
plus something extra. The extra term&nbsp;
given by 2 times 500 and 20 plus 3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.430 --> 00:05:16.980
times 3. This is a clue to how to set up&nbsp;
the Vedic algorithm. Here's how it works:

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:23.550
We write down the number that we're trying to&nbsp;
find the square root of, and we divide it into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:30.540
groups of two. We look at the leftmost group&nbsp;
of two and we find its square root, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:39.270
a number between 0 and 9. In this case, 27 is&nbsp;
close; the square root is 5. 5 squared is 25,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:45.420
and if we subtract 25 from here, the 2&nbsp;
comes down and then we also bring down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:54.810
the next pair of numbers. Now we have 235. This&nbsp;
corresponds to our initial guess of 500 squared.

00:05:57.030 --> 00:06:01.590
In the next step, what we have to do is we&nbsp;
are going to multiply what we have up here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.590 --> 00:06:09.690
the 5, by 2. 5 times 2 is 10, and we're going&nbsp;
to leave a little space for an extra digit.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:16.590
That's like that y, and we're going to try&nbsp;
to find an extra digit here, in this case 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:23.790
which has the property that this digit times 10&nbsp;
with a digit is pretty close to our remainder,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:33.480
235. So we're looking for a digit number&nbsp;
between 0 and 9 so that when you add it to 10,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:42.300
1 times digit and multiply it by the digit y, then&nbsp;
you are getting something that's close but less&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:50.130
than 235. If we tried 1, for example, we would&nbsp;
have 101 times 1, well that would be less than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:59.820
235. But 2 also works, 102 times 2 is 204, which&nbsp;
is less than 235. 3, however, would be too big&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:06.930
because 103 times 3 would be bigger than 235.&nbsp;
So 2 is the right number, and we subtract 204&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:15.090
and we get 31. Then we pull the 29 down, and then&nbsp;
we're going to repeat the same process with 329.

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:23.550
What we do is we take 52, which we've&nbsp;
already got, multiply it by 2, there's 104,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:29.910
and we add room for an extra digit. Now&nbsp;
we have to choose that digit so that when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.910 --> 00:07:34.680
we multiply the digit 2 times this number,&nbsp;
we get something that's less than or equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:41.400
to our remainder. It turns out that 3&nbsp;
exactly works, and when we subtract,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.400 --> 00:07:48.120
we get a remainder of 0, telling us that 523&nbsp;
is the square root of our original number.

00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:54.870
So let's look at another example. Alright, so&nbsp;
here's the number that we're trying to find the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.870 --> 00:08:01.560
square root of. We write that number down and&nbsp;
we group its digits into groups of 2. Looking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:07.290
at the leftmost group, its square root or&nbsp;
closest to it will be 7. 7 squared is 49,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.290 --> 00:08:16.650
we subtract and we get 22. Then we pull down the&nbsp;
next pair of digits for a remainder of 263. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:22.980
we're going to take the seven, multiply it by&nbsp;
2 for 14, and try to find the new digit, so y,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.980 --> 00:08:32.850
so that y times 14y is close to 263 but less than&nbsp;
it. Well, 1 is the best one because if we use 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:38.250
we get 142 times 2; that would be&nbsp;
bigger than this. So we put a 1 there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:46.620
1 times 141, we subtract, we get&nbsp;
122, and then we pull down the 85.

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:55.710
At this stage, we have 71 already. Multiply 71&nbsp;
by 2 right there, now we have to guess what the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.710 --> 00:09:03.540
new digit is so that this times this is less&nbsp;
than our remainder. Well, you have to adjust,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.540 --> 00:09:09.000
but there are only possibilities from 1&nbsp;
to 9, so it's not that bad. You guess 8,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:17.670
and 8 works. 8 times this is this number here.&nbsp;
Take the subtraction and you get 861. Finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.670 --> 00:09:25.170
we pull down the last pair of numbers, 96.&nbsp;
Take 718, multiply it by 2, right there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:32.940
and leave a space. Find a digit, 6 in this case,&nbsp;
so that's 6 times this number with a 6 there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:39.540
is less than or equal to our number or&nbsp;
remainder. Now it works out exactly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:45.330
so we get 0, meaning we've got an&nbsp;
exact square root. The answer is 7186.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:52.170
Next time, we're going to have a look at how&nbsp;
algebra helps us understand patterns generated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.170 --> 00:09:58.530
by special numbers. I hope you'll join me for&nbsp;
that. I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

